The flexible and self-healing amphiphilic copolymer (AP) was prepared by free radical polymerization method described in the previous study but with a target ratio between BA and NMA segments of 0.8:0.2 [47]. The success of synthesizing PBA0.8-co-PNMA0.2 with Mn of 60 kg mol−1 was confirmed by 1H NMR analysis and GPC measurement (
                           Figure S1 and S2
                        ). A modest preparation of the red-emissive film is as follows: 200 mg of PBA0.8-co-PNMA0.2 was dissolved in 1 mL of PGMEA solution containing low (0.2 mg BGQDs/1 mL PGMEA) or high (1 mg BGQDs/1mL PGMEA) concentrations of BGQDs. The resulting mixed solution was poured into a rectangular Teflon mold (with dimensions of GL × W × T is 25 mm × 10 mm × 0.25 mm) and dried at room temperature within 2 – 3 days. Then proceed with the cross-linking reaction via thermal annealing method at 90 °C for 6 h. The final film product is termed x% (w/w)@BGQDs/AP nanocomposite, where × is the percentage value of BGQDs in the AP system. Specifically, the obtained nanocomposite film containing 0.2 mg BGQDs was labeled 0.1% (w/w)@BGQDs/AP nanocomposite while containing 1 mg of BGQDs was labeled 0.5% (w/w)@BGQDs/AP nanocomposite.

Subsequently, Fig. 3 (c) demonstrates the excitation-dependence test performed on BGQDs, with excitation wavelengths ranging from 380 nm to 580 nm at 20 nm intervals. It was observed that BGQDs exhibited a remarkably low excitation dependence, as the emission center remained unchanged regardless of the excitation wavelength. This excitation-independent luminescent characteristic could be attributed to the uniform size and surface properties of the BGQDs [55]. Furthermore, the excitation-dependence test of BGQDs dispersed in Hexane and Toluene solutions also supported these findings ( Figure S7
